# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: calonarius
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:calonarius/agaricales] The **Agaricales** are an order of fungi in the division Basidiomycota.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] As originally conceived, the order contained all the agarics (gilled mushrooms), but subsequent research has shown that not all agarics are closely related and some belong in other orders, such as the Russulales and Boletales.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Conversely, DNA research has also shown that many non-agarics, including some of the clavarioid fungi (clubs and corals) and gasteroid fungi (puffballs and false truffles) belong within the Agaricales.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] The order has 46 extant families, more than 400 genera, and over 25,000 described species, along with six extinct genera known only from the fossil record.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Species in the Agaricales range from the familiar *Agaricus bisporus* (cultivated mushroom) and the deadly *Amanita virosa* (destroying angel) to the coral-like *Clavaria zollingeri* (violet coral) and bracket-like *Fistulina hepatica* (beefsteak fungus).
[src:calonarius/agaricales] In his three volumes of *Systema Mycologicum* published between 1821 and 1832, Elias Fries put almost all of the fleshy, gill-forming mushrooms in the genus *Agaricus*.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] He organized the large genus into "tribes", the names of many of which still exist as common genera of today.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Fries later elevated several of these tribes to generic level, but later authors—including Gillet, Karsten, Kummer, Quélet, and Staude—made most of the changes.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Fries based his classification on macroscopic characters of the fruit bodies and color of the spore print.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] His system had been widely used as it had the advantage that many genera could be readily identified based on characters observable in the field.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Fries's classification was later challenged when microscopic studies of basidiocarp structure, initiated by Fayod and Patouillard, demonstrated several of Fries's groupings were unnatural.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Singer treated three major groups within the Agaricales *sensu lato*: the Agaricales *sensu stricto*, Boletineae, and Russulales.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] These groups are still accepted by modern treatments based on DNA analysis, as the euagarics clade, bolete clade, and russuloid clade.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Molecular phylogenetics research has demonstrated that the euagarics clade is roughly equivalent to Singer's Agaricales *sensu stricto*.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] A large-scale study by Brandon Matheny and colleagues used nucleic acid sequences representing six gene regions from 238 species in 146 genera to explore the phylogenetic grouping within the Agaricales.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] The analysis showed that most of the species tested could be grouped into six clades that were named the Agaricoid, Tricholomatoid, Marasmioid, Pluteoid, Hygrophoroid and Plicaturopsidoid clades.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Molecular studies have shown that agarics are more divergent than once thought.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Agarics in the genera *Russula* and *Lactarius*, for example, belong to the order Russulales, whilst agarics in the genera *Paxillus* and *Hygrophoropsis* belong in the Boletales.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Conversely some genera with non-agaric fruit bodies, such as the puffballs, bird's nest fungi, and many clavarioid fungi, belong in the Agaricales.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Members of the Agaricales are ubiquitous, with species found in all continents.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] The great majority are terrestrial, in almost every habitat from woodland and grassland to deserts and dunes.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Agaricoid species were long thought to be solely terrestrial, until the 2005 discovery of *Psathyrella aquatica*, the only gilled mushroom known to fruit underwater.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] Species are variously saprotrophic or ectomycorrhizal, occasionally parasitic on plants or other fungi, and sometimes lichenized.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] the Agaricales include six monotypic fossil genera mostly found fossilized in amber.
[src:calonarius/agaricales] The three other species, *Aureofungus yaniguaensis*, *Coprinites dominicana* and *Protomycena electra* are known from single specimens found in the Dominican amber mines of Hispaniola.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] The **Agaricomycetes** are a class of fungi in the division Basidiomycota.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] The taxon is roughly identical to that defined for the **Homobasidiomycetes** (alternatively called holobasidiomycetes) by Hibbett & Thorn, with the inclusion of Auriculariales and Sebacinales.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] It includes not only mushroom-forming fungi, but also most species placed in the deprecated taxa Gasteromycetes and Homobasidiomycetes.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] Within the subdivision Agaricomycotina, which already excludes the smut and rust fungi, the Agaricomycetes can be further defined by the exclusion of the classes Tremellomycetes and Dacrymycetes, which are generally considered to be jelly fungi.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] However, a few former "jelly fungi", such as *Auricularia*, are classified in the Agaricomycetes.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] According to a 2008 estimate, Agaricomycetes include 17 orders, 100 families, 1147 genera, and about 21000 species.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] Modern molecular phylogenetic analyses have been since used to help define several new orders in the Agaricomycetes: Amylocorticiales, Jaapiales, Stereopsidales, and Lepidostromatales.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] Although morphology of the mushroom or fruit body (basidiocarp) was the basis of early classification of the Agaricomycetes, this is no longer the case.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] As an example, the distinction between the *Gasteromycetes* (including puffballs) and *Agaricomycetes* (most other agaric mushrooms) is no longer recognized as a natural one—various puffball species have apparently evolved independently from agaricomycete fungi.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] However, most mushroom guide books still group the puffballs or gasteroid forms separate from other mushrooms because the older Friesian classification is still convenient for categorizing fruit body forms.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] Similarly, modern classifications divide the gasteroid order Lycoperdales between Agaricales and Phallales.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] All members of the class produce basidiocarps which range in size from tiny cups a few millimeters across to a giant polypore (*Phellinus ellipsoideus*) greater than several meters across and weigh up to 500 kilograms (1,100 lb).
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] The group also includes what are arguably the largest and oldest individual organisms on earth: the mycelium of one individual *Armillaria gallica* has been estimated to extend over 15 hectares (37 acres) with a mass of 10,000 kilograms (22,000 pounds) and an age of 1,500 years.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] Agaricomycetes also have antibacterial properties.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] Agaricomycetes can help in research in treating bacteria.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] Nearly all species are terrestrial (a few are aquatic), occurring in a wide range of environments where most function as decayers, especially of wood.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] However, some species are pathogenic or parasitic, and yet others are symbiotic (i.e., mutualistic), these including the important ectomycorrhizal symbionts of forest trees.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] General discussions on the forms and life cycles of these fungi are developed in the article on mushrooms, in the treatments of the various orders (links in table at right), and in individual species accounts.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] The fruit bodies of Agaricomycetes are extremely rare in the fossil record, and the class does not yet pre-date the Early Cretaceous (146–100 Ma).
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] The oldest Agaricomycetes fossil, dating from the lower Cretaceous (130–125 Ma) is *Quatsinoporites*.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] It is a fragment of a poroid fruit body with features that suggest it could be a member of the family Hymenochaetaceae.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] Based on molecular clock analysis, the Agaricomycetes are estimated to be about 290 million years old.
[src:calonarius/agaricomycetes] There are many genera in the Agaricomycetes that have not been classified in any order or family.
[src:calonarius/aureonarius] The name *Aureonarius* derives from the Latin word '*aureus*' meaning golden and the suffix of the previous genus name *Cortinarius.* The name refers to the golden colour of the mushrooms in this genus.
[src:calonarius/aureonarius] As of January 2023, Species Fungorum accepted 18 species of *Aureonarius*.
[src:calonarius/aureonarius] *Aureonarius aurantiobrunneus* (Ammirati, Halling & Garnica) Niskanen & Liimat.
