[src:calonarius/austrocortinarius] There is currently no infrageneric classification proposed.
[src:calonarius/austrocortinarius] The name *Austrocortinarius* derives from '*austro*' meaning South and *Cortinarius*.
[src:calonarius/austrocortinarius] Currently the genus is only known from the Southern Hemisphere and so it is named in reference to this.
[src:calonarius/austrocortinarius] As of January 2023, Species Fungorum accepted 2 species of *Austrocortinarius*.
[src:calonarius/austrocortinarius] Basidiocarps in the genus *Austrocortinarius* are characterized by their white color and distinct, peronate universal veils leaving annular remnants when mature.
[src:calonarius/austrocortinarius] The basidiocarps may also possess a "rooting", subterranean stipe.
[src:calonarius/austrocortinarius] Currently, *Austrocortinarius* is only known from the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:calonarius/austrocortinarius] The genus has been documented in the following countries: Australia and New Zealand.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The **Basidiomycota** (/bəˌsɪdi.oʊmaɪˈkoʊtə/) are one of two large divisions that, together with the Ascomycota, constitute the subkingdom Dikarya (often referred to as the "**higher fungi**") within the kingdom Fungi.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Members are known as **basidiomycetes**.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] This division includes: agarics, puffballs, stinkhorns, bracket fungi, other polypores, jelly fungi, boletes, chanterelles, earth stars, smuts, bunts, rusts, mirror yeasts, and *Cryptococcus*, the human pathogenic yeast.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Basidiomycota are filamentous fungi composed of hyphae (except for basidiomycota-yeast) and reproduce sexually via the formation of specialized club-shaped end cells called basidia that normally bear external meiospores (usually four).
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] These specialized spores are called basidiospores.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] However, some Basidiomycota are obligate asexual reproducers.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] A 2007 classification, adopted by a coalition of 67 mycologists recognized three subphyla (Pucciniomycotina, Ustilaginomycotina, Agaricomycotina) and two other class level taxa (Wallemiomycetes, Entorrhizomycetes) outside of these, among the Basidiomycota.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] As now classified, the subphyla join and also cut across various obsolete taxonomic groups (see below) previously commonly used to describe Basidiomycota.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] According to a 2008 estimate, Basidiomycota comprise three subphyla (including six unassigned classes) 16 classes, 52 orders, 177 families, 1,589 genera, and 31,515 species.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Nonetheless these former concepts continue to be used as two types of growth habit groupings, the "mushrooms" (e.g.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] *Schizophyllum commune*) and the non-mushrooms (e.g.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] This sub-phyla also includes the "classic" mushrooms, polypores, corals, chanterelles, crusts, puffballs and stinkhorns.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The three classes in the Agaricomycotina are the Agaricomycetes, the Dacrymycetes, and the Tremellomycetes.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The class Wallemiomycetes is not yet placed in a subdivision, but recent genomic evidence suggests that it is a sister group of Agaricomycotina.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The Pucciniomycotina include the rust fungi, the insect parasitic/symbiotic genus *Septobasidium*, a former group of smut fungi (in the Microbotryomycetes, which includes mirror yeasts), and a mixture of odd, infrequently seen, or seldom recognized fungi, often parasitic on plants.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The eight classes in the Pucciniomycotina are Agaricostilbomycetes, Atractiellomycetes, Classiculomycetes, Cryptomycocolacomycetes, Cystobasidiomycetes, Microbotryomycetes, Mixiomycetes, and Pucciniomycetes.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The Ustilaginomycotina are most (but not all) of the former smut fungi and the Exobasidiales.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The classes of the Ustilaginomycotina are the Exobasidiomycetes, the Entorrhizomycetes, and the Ustilaginomycetes.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Unlike animals and plants which have readily recognizable male and female counterparts, Basidiomycota (except for the Rust (Pucciniales)) tend to have mutually indistinguishable, compatible haploids which are usually mycelia being composed of filamentous hyphae.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Typically haploid Basidiomycota mycelia fuse via plasmogamy and then the compatible nuclei migrate into each other's mycelia and pair up with the resident nuclei.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Karyogamy is delayed, so that the compatible nuclei remain in pairs, called a dikaryon.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The hyphae are then said to be dikaryotic.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Conversely, the haploid mycelia are called monokaryons.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Often, the dikaryotic mycelium is more vigorous than the individual monokaryotic mycelia, and proceeds to take over the substrate in which they are growing.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The dikaryons can be long-lived, lasting years, decades, or centuries.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The monokaryons are *neither* male nor female.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] They have either a *bipolar* (*unifactorial*) or a *tetrapolar* (*bifactorial*) mating system.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] However, there are sometimes more than two possible alleles for a given locus, and in such species, depending on the specifics, over 90% of monokaryons could be compatible with each other.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The maintenance of the dikaryotic status in dikaryons in many Basidiomycota is facilitated by the formation of clamp connections that physically appear to help coordinate and re-establish pairs of compatible nuclei following synchronous mitotic nuclear divisions.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] In a typical Basidiomycota lifecycle the long lasting dikaryons periodically (seasonally or occasionally) produce basidia, the specialized usually club-shaped end cells, in which a pair of compatible nuclei fuse (karyogamy) to form a diploid cell.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Meiosis follows shortly with the production of 4 haploid nuclei that migrate into 4 external, usually apical basidiospores.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Typically the basidiospores are ballistic, hence they are sometimes also called ballistospores.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] In most species, the basidiospores disperse and each can start a new haploid mycelium, continuing the lifecycle.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Basidia are microscopic but they are often produced on or in multicelled large fructifications called basidiocarps or basidiomes, or fruitbodies, variously called mushrooms, puffballs, etc.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Ballistic basidiospores are formed on sterigmata which are tapered spine-like projections on basidia, and are typically curved, like the horns of a bull.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] In some Basidiomycota the spores are not ballistic, and the sterigmata may be straight, reduced to stubs, or absent.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The basidiospores of these non-ballistosporic basidia may either bud off, or be released via dissolution or disintegration of the basidia.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] In summary, meiosis takes place in a diploid basidium.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Each one of the four haploid nuclei migrates into its own basidiospore.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The basidiospores are ballistically discharged and start new haploid mycelia called monokaryons.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] There are no males or females, rather there are compatible thalli with multiple compatibility factors.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Plasmogamy between compatible individuals leads to delayed karyogamy leading to establishment of a dikaryon.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The dikaryon is long lasting but ultimately gives rise to either fruitbodies with basidia or directly to basidia without fruitbodies.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The paired dikaryon in the basidium fuse (i.e. karyogamy takes place).
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The diploid basidium begins the cycle again.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Many variations occur: some variations are self-compatible and spontaneously form dikaryons without a separate compatible thallus being involved.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] These fungi are said to be homothallic, versus the normal heterothallic species with mating types.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Others are secondarily homothallic, in that two compatible nuclei following meiosis migrate into each basidiospore, which is then dispersed as a pre-existing dikaryon.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Often such species form only two spores per basidium, but that too varies.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Following meiosis, mitotic divisions can occur in the basidium.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Multiple numbers of basidiospores can result, including odd numbers via degeneration of nuclei, or pairing up of nuclei, or lack of migration of nuclei.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Occasionally, monokaryons of some taxa can form morphologically fully formed basidiomes and anatomically correct basidia and ballistic basidiospores in the absence of dikaryon formation, diploid nuclei, and meiosis.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] A rare few number of taxa have extended diploid lifecycles, but can be common species.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Examples exist in the mushroom genera *Armillaria* and *Xerula*, both in the Physalacriaceae.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Occasionally, basidiospores are not formed and parts of the "basidia" act as the dispersal agents, e.g. the peculiar mycoparasitic jelly fungus, *Tetragoniomyces* or the entire "basidium" acts as a "spore", e.g. in some false puffballs (*Scleroderma*).
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Other variations occur: some as standard lifecycles (that themselves have variations within variations) within specific orders.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Rusts (Pucciniales, previously known as Uredinales) at their greatest complexity, produce five different types of spores on two different host plants in two unrelated host families.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Such rusts are heteroecious (requiring two hosts) and macrocyclic (producing all five spores types).
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] By convention, the stages and spore states are numbered by Roman numerals.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Typically, basidiospores infect host one, also known as the alternate or sexual host, and the mycelium forms pycnidia, which are miniature, flask-shaped, hollow, submicroscopic bodies embedded in the host tissue (such as a leaf).
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] This stage, numbered "0", produces single-celled spores that ooze out in a sweet liquid and that act as nonmotile spermatia, and also protruding receptive hyphae.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Insects and probably other vectors such as rain carry the spermatia from spermagonium to spermagonium, cross inoculating the mating types.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Once crossed, the dikaryons are established and a second spore stage is formed, numbered "I" and called aecia, which form dikaryotic aeciospores in dry chains in inverted cup-shaped bodies embedded in host tissue.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] These aeciospores then infect the second host, known as the primary or asexual host (in macrocyclic rusts).
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] On the primary host a repeating spore stage is formed, numbered "II", the urediospores in dry pustules called uredinia.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Urediospores are dikaryotic and can infect the same host that produced them.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] They repeatedly infect this host over the growing season.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] At the end of the season, a fourth spore type, the teliospore, is formed.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] It is thicker-walled and serves to overwinter or to survive other harsh conditions.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] It does not continue the infection process, rather it remains dormant for a period and then germinates to form basidia (stage "IV"), sometimes called a promycelium.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] In the Pucciniales, the basidia are cylindrical and become 3-septate after meiosis, with each of the 4 cells bearing one basidiospore each.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The basidiospores disperse and start the infection process on host 1 again.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Autoecious rusts complete their life-cycles on one host instead of two, and microcyclic rusts cut out one or more stages.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The characteristic part of the life-cycle of smuts is the thick-walled, often darkly pigmented, ornate, teliospore that serves to survive harsh conditions such as overwintering and also serves to help disperse the fungus as dry diaspores.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The teliospores are initially dikaryotic but become diploid via karyogamy.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Meiosis takes place at the time of germination.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] A promycelium is formed that consists of a short hypha (equated to a basidium).
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] In some smuts such as *Mycosarcoma maydis* the nuclei migrate into the promycelium that becomes septate (i.e., divided into cellular compartments separated by cell walls called *septa*), and haploid yeast-like conidia/basidiospores sometimes called sporidia, bud off laterally from each cell.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] In various smuts, the yeast phase may proliferate, or they may fuse, or they may infect plant tissue and become hyphal.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] In other smuts, such as *Tilletia caries*, the elongated haploid basidiospores form apically, often in compatible pairs that fuse centrally resulting in H-shaped diaspores which are by then dikaryotic.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Eventually the host is infected by infectious hyphae.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Many variations on these general themes occur.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Smuts with both a yeast phase and an infectious hyphal state are examples of dimorphic Basidiomycota.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] In plant parasitic taxa, the saprotrophic phase is normally the yeast while the infectious stage is hyphal.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] However, there are examples of animal and human parasites where the species are dimorphic but it is the yeast-like state that is infectious.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The genus *Filobasidiella* forms basidia on hyphae but the main infectious stage is more commonly known by the anamorphic yeast name *Cryptococcus*, e.g.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] *Cryptococcus neoformans* and *Cryptococcus gattii*.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] The dimorphic Basidiomycota with yeast stages and the pleiomorphic rusts are examples of fungi with anamorphs, which are the asexual stages.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Some Basidiomycota are only known as anamorphs.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Many are called basidiomycetous yeasts, which differentiates them from ascomycetous yeasts in the Ascomycota.
[src:calonarius/basidiomycota] Aside from yeast anamorphs and uredinia, aecia, and pycnidia, some Basidiomycota form other distinctive anamorphs as parts of their life cycles.
[src:calonarius/calonarius-aureofulvus] It was described by Austrian mycologist Meinhard Michael Moser in 1952 who classified it as *Cortinarius aureofulvus* and then reclassified it as *Phlegmacium aureofulvum* in 1960.
[src:calonarius/calonarius-aureofulvus] In 2022 the species was transferred from *Cortinarius* and reclassified as *Calonarius aureofulvus* based on genomic data.
[src:calonarius/calonarius-cupreorufus] In 2022 the species was transferred from *Cortinarius* and reclassified as *Calonarius cupreorufus* based on genomic data.
[src:calonarius/calonarius] The name *Calonarius* derives from the combination of the genus name *Cortinarius* and the section name *Calochroi* in which these species were placed prior to the reclassification.
[src:calonarius/calonarius] As of January 2023, Species Fungorum accepted 133 species of *Calonarius*.
[src:calonarius/calonarius] *Calonarius albertii* (Dima, Frøslev & T.S.
[src:calonarius/calonarius] *Calonarius albidolilacinus* (Ammirati, Bojantchev, Beug, Liimat., Niskanen & Garnica) Niskanen & Liimat.
[src:calonarius/calonarius] *Calonarius alnobetulae* (Kühner) Niskanen & Liimat.
[src:calonarius/calonarius] *Calonarius amabilis* (Bojantchev, Ammirati & Pastorino) Niskanen & Liimat.
[src:calonarius/calonarius] *Calonarius anetholens* (Ammirati, Garnica, Bojantchev, Beug, Liimat. & Niskanen) Niskanen & Liimat.
[src:calonarius/calonarius] *Calonarius atrovirens* (Kalchbr.) Niskanen & Liimat.
